#Approach:

Longest Consecutive Sequence – HashSet Approach

Sabse pehle saare elements ko HashSet me store kar lo taki O(1) lookup mil sake.

Phir set ko traverse karo aur har element ke liye check karo
ki kya wo sequence ka starting element hai.
Koi element tab starting element hoga jab set me uska previous element (it-1) present na ho.

Agar starting element mil gaya, to usse consecutive sequence count karna start karo
(it+1, it+2, it+3...) jab tak set me milte rahe.

Har sequence ka length count karo aur maximum length update karte raho.

Important:
Har element se sequence start nahi karte,
sirf un elements se start karte hain jinke pehle wala element set me nahi hota.
Isse time complexity O(n) ho jaati hai.

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(n)

#Code:

class Solution {
    public int longestConsecutive(int[] nums) {
        int n = nums.length;

        if(n == 0){
            return 0;
        }

        HashSet<Integer> set = new HashSet<>();
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
            set.add(nums[i]);
        }

        int len = 1;

        for(int it : set){
            if(!set.contains(it-1)){
                int cnt = 1;
                int x = it+1;
                while(set.contains(x)){
                    cnt++;
                    x=x+1;
                }
                len = Math.max(len, cnt);
            }
        }
        return len;
    }
}
